    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption><em>Pixel 4 Selfie camera</em></figcaption>
      
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

</div>
<p id="0XX5ve">And Apple caught up on that front. After all these comparisons, I can’t pick a winner because when it comes to still photography, these phones each have their strengths and (increasingly fewer) weaknesses. You’d have to make a spreadsheet to parse them all out, and even if you did, picking a winner would be unsatisfying because they each produce aesthetically different photos, which is entirely subjective. The Pixel has its look, and it nails it almost every time. The iPhone is a little more neutral. This is basically Nikon vs Canon — or maybe Kodak vs Fujifilm in the film days. </p>
<p id="2dngfe">If you forced me to just pick a winner right now, I have to admit that the iPhone 11 Pro gives you much more versatility: it has an ultrawide for taking more fun shots, and it’s way better at video.</p>
<p id="WV80pg">The real bottom line is that you shouldn’t base your decision to buy one or the other phone based on the quality of their photos.</p>
